module MeasureLen

(* PROVE V2.1 — the measure DECLARATION.  What it buys, exactly, and no more.

   Under V1 this file was not an unproved program; it was a REFINEMENT ERROR.
   `len` had no declaration, so it had no sort, so `len(v) > 0` was not a
   predicate at all — `_int_term`'s sort guard threw it out, and rightly: an
   unsorted symbol has no business in an ordering.  The only names a V1 predicate
   could apply were the program's own functions, which is a strange rule when you
   say it out loud, and the strangeness is what the measure declaration removes.

   So V2.1's win is smaller than it sounds and bigger than it looks: DECLARING the
   measure is what lets its name into a contract in the first place.  The word
   `len` now means something to the logic — it is an Int-sorted symbol, and the
   checker knows one equation per constructor for it.

   V2.1 does NOT hand those equations to the solver.  That is V2.2, and this file
   is its thermometer.  The call in `main` owes exactly one obligation —

       len(Cons(3, Cons(4, Nil))) > 0

   — and it is UNPROVED, honestly: the equations exist, the solver has not been
   shown them, so `len` is still nothing but a symbol.  It is true, it is not
   provable, and the checker says so rather than guessing.  The day V2.2
   instantiates the equations at the terms the program mentions, this file goes
   green with no other change — which is what makes it a test and not a comment.

   And it RUNS.  Measures are ghost: they live in `Program.measures`, never in
   `Program.decls`, so infer.py and the CEK machine never see one.  Erasure by
   construction, with the corollary for free — calling `len` from real code is an
   unbound-name error from HM, not a rule anybody had to write.

   Expected output:
     3 *)

type List a = | Nil | Cons of a, List(a)

measure len(xs : List(Int)) : Int =
  match xs with
  | Nil           => 0
  | Cons(_, rest) => 1 + len(rest)
  end

fn head(xs : {v : List(Int) | len(v) > 0}) : Int =
  match xs with
  | Nil        => 0
  | Cons(x, _) => x
  end

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  print(io, show(head(Cons(3, Cons(4, Nil)))))
